<subSubSection id="D82C10DE060D1D0FEFE483BF06437000" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="F17F099E092524585A9668FAE6101AA5" pageId="0" pageNumber="15">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1F779AFF4CA43679DA833DF2968167A5" pageId="0" pageNumber="15">In reference to Italy, the country where the holotype was found.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="17CE35E4D520422F04F3C549A9603D1D" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="126C4E33CB99CB82C0CD7C426C59C67B" pageId="0" pageNumber="15">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E9B4CE86BF1A0A05515557F0119DB9D4" pageId="0" pageNumber="15">
Sexual morph: Stromata solitary to gregarious, inmersed to erumpent, fusiform, with long axis broken at the top by one or two cracks, 0.5-4 
<normalizedToken id="3105235B62B285BF8ED39F6065B17CE8" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2-0.5 mm (n = 20). Ascomata uniseriate or irregularly arranged beneath stromata, pseudothecial, black, globose to subglobose with a flattened base, 150-200 
<normalizedToken id="7DD9EF127DEBB962F6D2292BCBFBEA79" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
high 
<normalizedToken id="5CB59D5E322BCCE979301CFB88C74805" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
230-300 
<normalizedToken id="19699A5AB84EA38E12928A54943AF54A" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
wide. Peridium composed of 5 or 6 layers of brown cells arranged in textura angularis, with a conspicuous peryphisate ostiole. Hamathecium paraphyses hyphae-like. Asci broadly cylindrical, clavate or subglobose, pedicel indistinct, apically rounded (70
<normalizedToken id="2615DB6E42528A64AB72C37A3AD10C9C" originalValue="–)72–93(–">-)72-93(-</normalizedToken>
96) 
<normalizedToken id="F70495A30F44279C0589EA775DD688F3" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(14
<normalizedToken id="8C1E71FE9BD8F57E8AA97F547B38B255" originalValue="–)15–18(–">-)15-18(-</normalizedToken>
20) 
<normalizedToken id="83E204A2C7A45AA6EB89057299943F38" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(n = 30). Ascospores apiosporic, clavate to fusiform with narrowly rounded ends, composed of a large upper cell and small lower cell, hyaline, smooth-walled, surrounded by a gelatinose sheath, measuring (20
<normalizedToken id="30687CB0A6729770053352E346941F08" originalValue="–)21–25(–">-)21-25(-</normalizedToken>
26) 
<normalizedToken id="3074485A82DF36E43900A6741D1642AB" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(5
<normalizedToken id="B9A722270F56C810042F99727030C7F7" originalValue="–)6–">-)6-</normalizedToken>
9(-10) 
<normalizedToken id="6CBC800C9B21CB3BD3AC1BC29D6370FB" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
, basal cell 3-5 
<normalizedToken id="B5A89D98046821F510E109CC9D72B8EA" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(n = 45). Asexual morph: Mycelium consisting of smooth, hyaline, branched, septate hyphae 1.5-4 
<normalizedToken id="B58B6B202F58B89D3D6AA18FB6652302" originalValue="µm">µm</normalizedToken>
in diameter. Conidiophores straight or flexuous, cylindrical, colourless except for the thick brown transversal septa, smooth-walled, 10-50 
<normalizedToken id="55994E9F324F720E777E02DA66E21D55" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-3 
<normalizedToken id="5F18BD3EB3728FD2D72EB0141D0A8432" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
. Conidiogenous cells ampuliform, cylindrical or doliform, hyaline to brown, (3
<normalizedToken id="00E57705D658FB3CBDB1836BD4B73A2B" originalValue="–)4–7(–">-)4-7(-</normalizedToken>
9) 
<normalizedToken id="185C61DE1B4E7742F09B3C0B624E228E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(1.5
<normalizedToken id="87839821E524FCE4A564C3E3DDC601B6" originalValue="–)2–3(–">-)2-3(-</normalizedToken>
5) 
<normalizedToken id="E6B850A51C6A53B9FB30A4B7FC4CAF6E" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(n = 30). Conidia brown, smooth, globose in face view, lenticular in side view, 4-6 
<normalizedToken id="7583C7830FE815B81DE0DB0882ABC853" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-4 
<normalizedToken id="E20BFBC3A71C4F14605CF7B1E9EF68A3" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(n = 65), with a pale equatorial slit. Culture characteristics: on MEA 2%, sparse aerial mycelia, surface dirty white, reverse pale yellowish.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="32EB140CCBA95E91C77C5D129465EF38" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="7BB3E7A0A391E56BA6C3279DF641AEF9" pageId="0" pageNumber="15">Type.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="19952913B7F929EBCAB1B709B2385BE2" pageId="0" pageNumber="15">
Italy: Sicily: On dead culms of 
<taxonomicName id="38A721AAFDD64088D9E5144182CA5E66" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Arundo" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Arundo donax" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="donax">Arundo donax</taxonomicName>
, 19 June 2016, H. Voglmayr (MA-Fungi 91733 holotype, AP221017 isotype, CBS 145138 ex-type culture).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="957F22D957929303F38B87011166AA3E" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" type="notes">
<paragraph id="C593506F63E71371067A664D25BA0946" pageId="0" pageNumber="15">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CB08E6D0D51EDFAE02FBDC2A27E43CDC" pageId="0" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName id="FEDE95B996F1C5F3A07BBD0DF0E00572" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Apiosporaceae" genus="Arthrinium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Arthrinium italicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="italicum">Arthrinium italicum</taxonomicName>
is phylogenetically close to 
<taxonomicName id="EDAA48CB50CF2E1BFA919ADAB4C8CF47" genus="A." lsidName="A. thailandicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" rank="species" species="thailandicum">A. thailandicum</taxonomicName>
, and to a lesser extent to 
<taxonomicName id="56BAE2559EA4931FEB17D24ABE6811D6" genus="A." lsidName="A. malaysianum" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" rank="species" species="malaysianum">A. malaysianum</taxonomicName>
. Stromata of 
<taxonomicName id="904C5FE5548CA2F9C3D339F9024CBC2C" genus="A." lsidName="A. thailandicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" rank="species" species="thailandicum">A. thailandicum</taxonomicName>
are smaller than those of 
<taxonomicName id="9364D4DDDE8301B33E89B220A77A2F36" genus="A." lsidName="A. italicum" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" rank="species" species="italicum">A. italicum</taxonomicName>
, measuring 0.45-0.99 
<normalizedToken id="6C8E748D72246C1CC14D9CEF83595E11" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.3-0.55 mm, ascomata are perithecical, its conidiogenous cells are longer (11.5-39 
<normalizedToken id="D16BA8B128E16855A78F9E67CC17049B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-3.5 
<normalizedToken id="EED1ABD80EA80C5B6A8BE02E2962FE8F" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) and branched, and conidia measure 5-9 
<normalizedToken id="D236C50E0A36936685AFBB9E5CBB069A" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-8 
<normalizedToken id="4C439FEBBE0120ED59278D9C8EE41C03" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
. The conidia of 
<taxonomicName id="082AEF1F23CFEC8331F1FE03BF5FF486" genus="A." lsidName="A. malaysianum" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" rank="species" species="malaysianum">A. malaysianum</taxonomicName>
are similar in size, but this species does not produce conidiophores.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CC3308C40FADA72E8B2039019571B5E9" pageId="0" pageNumber="15" type="materials_examined">
